[2] Minnesota, Iowa, and South Dakota: turkey
Date: Tue 13 Dec 2022
Source: Wattagnet [edited]
https://www.wattagnet.com/articles/46348-avian-flu-hits-flock-of-298-100-minnesota-turkeys


Avian flu hits flock of 298 100 Minnesota turkeys
-------------------------------------------------
The latest case of highly pathogenic avian influenza (HPAI) to be confirmed in Minnesota involved a flock of 298 100 commercial meat turkeys. The latest case, according to the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service (APHIS), was confirmed on 12 Dec 2022 and was located in Wadena County.

With this detection, Minnesota has now had 81 commercial poultry flocks affected by HPAI in 2022, resulting in the loss of nearly 4.2 million birds. However, this is the 1st operation to be affected by the virus this year [2022] in Wadena County.

Avian flu hits 7th Iowa turkey flock
------------------------------------
A new case of HPAI was confirmed in a commercial turkey flock in Ida County, Iowa, making it the 7th turkey flock to be affected by the virus so far in December [2022]. The Iowa Department of Agriculture and Land Stewardship (IDAL) announced the latest case in a press release, issued on 12 Dec 2022. This is the first case of HPAI to be confirmed in Ida County in 2022.

The other counties to have HPAI cases in December [2022] are Buena Vista, Sac and Cherokee. Each of those counties has had 2 confirmed cases this month [December 2022]. IDAL has not disclosed the size of any of those flocks, but APHIS has released information concerning 3 of those cases. A case confirmed on 5 Dec 2022 in Buena Vista County involved 40 700 turkeys. A case confirmed 7 Dec 2022 in Sac County involved 40 000 turkeys, while a case confirmed that same day [7 Dec 2022] in Cherokee County involved 105 000 turkeys.

Iowa has lost more birds to HPAI in 2022 than any other state. Not including losses from the 4 most recent cases in Iowa, the state has lost 15 682 300 birds to HPAI.

Cases continue in South Dakota
------------------------------
APHIS announced the presence of HPAI was confirmed in a commercial meat turkey flock in Hanson County, South Dakota, on 12 Dec 2022 affecting 23 900 turkeys.

This is the fourth case for Hanson County and the 59th for South Dakota in 2022.

[byline: Roy Graber]

