[3] Indiana (Martin County, Daviess County): turkey
Date: Wed 14 Dec 2022
Source: Wattagnet [edited]
https://www.wattagnet.com/articles/46358-another-potential-avian-flu-case-found-in-indiana-turkeys


Another potential avian flu case found in Indiana turkeys
---------------------------------------------------------
A commercial turkey flock in Martin County, Indiana, was depopulated after it was determined to be at high risk of exposure to highly pathogenic avian influenza (HPAI).

The flock in question involved 27 083 turkeys, according to an email from the Indiana State Board of Animal Health (BOAH). The Martin County flock was depopulated because it "is associated with" another commercial turkey flock in Daviess County, which the BOAH reported as a presumptive positive case of HPAI on 11 Dec 2022.

BOAH further stated the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) National Veterinary Services Laboratory confirmed a diagnosis of the H5N1 virus in the Daviess County flock, which included 11 394 turkeys.

According to the USDA Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service (APHIS), Indiana has had 9 cases of HPAI in commercial poultry flocks so far in 2022, but the figure does not include the Daviess County or Martin County turkey flocks. Of those 9 cases, 6 involved commercial meat turkeys, 2 involved commercial duck breeders and 1 involved commercial meat ducks.

To learn more about HPAI cases in commercial poultry flocks in the United States and Canada, see an interactive map at https://www.wattagnet.com/articles/44650-track-2022-avian-influenza-outbreaks-in-north-american-poultry.

[byline: Roy Graber]

